rmed by interviews with activists from all walks of life-city dwellers, villagers, political dissidents, children of military families, wage laborers, shopkeepers, beauticians, spirit mediums, lawyers, students-Chua details the vivid particulars of the LGBT activist experience founding a movement first among exiles and migrants and then in Myanmar's cities, towns, and countryside. A distinct political and emotional culture of activism took shape, fusing shared emotions and cultural bearings with legal and political ideas about human rights. For this network of activists, human rights moved hearts and minds and crafted a transformative web of friendship, fellowship, and affection among queer Burmese. Chua's investigation provides crucial insights into the intersection of emotions and interpersonal relationships with law, rights, and social movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aSexual minoritiesxCivil rightsxBurma. 0aSexual minoritiesxCivil rightszBurma. 0aSexual minoritiesxPolitical activityxBurma. 0aSexual minoritiesxPolitical activityzBurma. 4aLGBT rights. 4aMyanmar. 4aemotions. 4ahuman rights. 4ainterpersonal relationships. 4alaw and society. 4aqueer activism. 4asocial movements. 4asociolegal studies. 7aLAW / Civil Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360745340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503607453.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles